For small strings, a copy is not only faster but more multithreading friendly.<p>Keep in mind that on a 64-bit architecture a view is at least 16 bytes large and that small strings can be copied to the stack resulting in better locality and reduced memory usage.<p>Last but not least, with copy elision, your temporaries might not even exist in the first place.<p>Example:<p><pre><code>    std::string data;
    // ...
    auto str = data.substr(2, 3);
    // pretty sure str will be optimized away
    if (str[0] == &#x27;a&#x27;)</code></pre>
